1. KPI Cards Creation (Executive Summary)
Created individual KPI cards using the Card (New) visual to summarize key business metrics.
Steps:
    • Created DAX measures using DISTINCTCOUNT, SUM, and AVERAGE
    • Used Card (New) visual, placing one measure per card
    • Configured Callout Value formatting for clarity
KPIs Created:
    • Total Customers: Distinct count of Customer ID
    • Locations: Distinct count of Location (state)
    • Items Purchased: Distinct count of Item Purchased
    • Average Age: Average of customer age, rounded to whole number
    • Total Purchased Cost: Sum of Purchase Amount (USD), displayed in thousands
Purpose:
    • Provide a high-level overview of customer base, geographic coverage, product diversity, demographics, and revenue

2. Highlight Table – Customer Distribution by Location
Created a highlight table to visualize customer distribution across states.
Steps:
    • Inserted a Table visual
    • Added Location and Customer ID fields
    • Set Customer ID aggregation to Count or Distinct Count
    • Applied conditional formatting using Data Bars on customer count
    • Sorted table in descending order by customer count
Purpose:
    • Quickly identify states with higher or lower customer concentration
    • Enhance readability using visual indicators within table cells

3. Stacked Bar Chart – Customers by Shipping Type and Purchase Frequency
Built a stacked bar chart to analyze customer behavior across shipping methods and purchase frequency.
Steps:
    • Selected Stacked Bar Chart visual
    • Assigned Shipping Type to Y-axis
    • Assigned Frequency of Purchases to Legend
    • Used Total Customers (distinct count measure) as X-axis value
    • Enabled data labels for customer count visibility
Purpose:
    • Compare customer distribution across shipping options
    • Identify how purchase frequency varies by shipping method

4. Bar Chart – Purchase Amount by Category and Season
Created a bar chart to analyze spending patterns across product categories and seasons.
Steps:
    • Selected Bar Chart visual
    • Assigned Product Category to Axis
    • Assigned Total Purchase Amount to Values
    • Used Season as Legend
    • Enabled data labels to display purchase amounts for each season
Purpose:
    • Identify seasonal purchasing trends
    • Compare revenue contribution by product category

5. Line Chart – Age vs Average Purchase Amount (With Min/Max Highlight)
Developed a line chart to show the relationship between customer age and average purchase amount.
Steps:
    • Selected Line Chart visual
    • Assigned Age to X-axis
    • Assigned Average Purchase Amount measure to Y-axis
    • Created additional DAX measures to identify maximum and minimum average purchase amounts
    • Added Max and Min measures to the chart to label peak and lowest spending ages
    • Enabled data labels only for highlighted points
Purpose:
    • Analyze spending behavior across age groups
    • Identify peak spending age and lowest spending age

6. Pie Chart – Total Purchase Amount by Gender
Built a pie chart to compare total spending by gender.
Steps:
    • Selected Pie Chart visual
    • Assigned Gender to Legend
    • Assigned Total Purchase Amount (SUM measure) to Values
    • Enabled data labels showing value and percentage of total
Purpose:
    • Compare contribution of each gender to overall revenue
    • Provide an intuitive breakdown of spending distribution

7. Matrix Table – Shipping Type vs Purchase Frequency
Created a matrix to complement the stacked bar chart with detailed numeric values.
Steps:
    • Inserted Matrix visual
    • Assigned Shipping Type to Rows
    • Assigned Frequency of Purchases to Columns
    • Used Total Customers measure as Values
    • Disabled unnecessary totals and gridlines for clarity
Purpose:
    • Provide detailed customer counts supporting the visual analysis
    • Enable precise comparison across customer segments

8. Dashboard Save and Reusability
Ensured dashboard persistence and reusability.
Steps:
    • Saved the report as a PBIX file
    • Enabled Auto Recovery settings
    • Verified that all visuals, measures, and formatting persist when reopening the file
Purpose:
    • Maintain dashboard consistency
    • Enable future enhancements and reuse
